
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `dscextract` baraye gereftan (extract) va be dast avardane etela'at az file-haye DSC (Desktop Services Command) estefade mishavad. In file-ha dar macOS baraye negahdari etela'at metadata file-ha, mesle thumbnail-ha va comment-ha be kar miravand. Ba `dscextract`, shoma mitoonid in etela'at ro be dast biarid va estefade konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `dscextract -a`  --> 📦 Gereftane hameye etela'at metadata mojood.
    🔹 `dscextract -t type file.dsc` --> 🖼️ Gereftane yek no'e khass az metadata (meslan, thumbnail). Type bayad thumbnail ya comment bashad.
    🔹 `dscextract -o output_folder file.dsc` --> 📂 Specify a directory to store the extracted files

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ dscextract -a example.dsc

    🔹 Gereftane hameye etela'at az file example.dsc va zakhire dar directory jari.

    $ dscextract -t thumbnail image.dsc

    🔹 Gereftane thumbnail az file image.dsc va zakhire dar directory jari.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ dscextract -t thumbnail myimage.dsc

    🔹 In dastoor thumbnail az file `myimage.dsc` ra gerefte va an ra dar directory jari zakhire mikonad. Agar thumbnail mojood nabashad, hich chizi zakhire nemishavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `dscextract` command is used to extract information from DSC (Desktop Services Command) files. These files are used on macOS to store metadata about files, such as thumbnails and comments. With `dscextract`, you can retrieve and use this information.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `dscextract -a`  --> 📦 Extract all available metadata.
    🔹 `dscextract -t type file.dsc` --> 🖼️ Extract a specific type of metadata (e.g., thumbnail). Type must be thumbnail or comment.
    🔹 `dscextract -o output_folder file.dsc` --> 📂 Specify a directory to store the extracted files

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ dscextract -a example.dsc

    🔹 Extracts all information from the file example.dsc and saves it in the current directory.

    $ dscextract -t thumbnail image.dsc

    🔹 Extracts the thumbnail from the file image.dsc and saves it in the current directory.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ dscextract -t thumbnail myimage.dsc

    🔹 This command extracts the thumbnail from the file `myimage.dsc` and saves it to the current directory. If no thumbnail exists, nothing will be saved.
